Service Level Agreements (SLAs):

Availability: Define the percentage of uptime guaranteed for the cloud data lake service. For example, 99.9% uptime.
Performance: Specify response times for queries and data access.
Scalability: Define how the service scales in response to increased demand.
Data Durability: Guarantee the durability of data stored in the data lake, typically measured in terms of data loss over time.
Support: Outline the level of support provided by the cloud service provider for any issues or inquiries.
Security: Detail the security measures in place to protect data in transit and at rest.
Data Catalog Requirements:

Metadata Management: Ability to capture, store, and manage metadata for all data assets within the data lake.
Data Discovery: Facilitate easy discovery of data assets by users through search and browsing capabilities.
Data Lineage: Track the origins, transformations, and movement of data within the data lake.
Data Quality: Provide mechanisms for assessing and maintaining data quality, including data profiling and data cleansing capabilities.
Access Control: Implement fine-grained access controls to ensure that only authorized users can view and interact with specific data assets.
Integration: Support integration with other data management tools and platforms, such as data governance tools and analytics platforms.
Collaboration: Enable collaboration features to allow users to annotate, tag, and share data assets with others.
Other Requirements:

Data Ingestion: Support various methods of data ingestion, including batch and real-time streaming.
Data Transformation: Provide tools and services for transforming raw data into a usable format for analysis and reporting.
Data Governance: Implement policies and procedures for managing data quality, security, and compliance within the data lake.
Cost Management: Offer features for monitoring and optimizing costs associated with storage and processing resources.
Interoperability: Ensure compatibility with existing data management systems and tools to facilitate integration and data exchange.
Disaster Recovery: Implement mechanisms for backup and disaster recovery to minimize the risk of data loss in the event of a failure or outage.
